  "prompt": "Who investigates the Federal Bureau of Investigation?",
  "response": "The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) is investigated by various entities, depending on the nature of the investigation. Some of them include:\n\n1. **Inspectors General**: The Department of Justice (DOJ) has an Office of the Inspector General (OIG) that can investigate the FBI's activities, particularly concerning allegations of misconduct or abuse of power.\n\n2. **Congress**: Congressional committees have the authority to conduct investigations into the FBI's operations, oversight, and activities. They can hold hearings and request documents related to the FBI's actions.\n\n3. **Internal Affairs**: The FBI has its own internal review systems and processes, including a professional responsibility program that investigates allegations of misconduct by its personnel.\n\n4. **External Agencies**: In certain situations, other federal or state law enforcement agencies may be involved in investigating the FBI, especially if there are allegations that cross organizational lines or involve serious misconduct.\n\n5. **The Public**: In some cases, civil rights organizations, watchdog groups, and the media may conduct investigations and report on issues related to the FBI, influencing public perception and prompting inquiries.\n\nThese investigations ensure accountability and transparency within the FBI and help maintain public trust in its operations.",
